11118	sci.crypt	Xref: cantaloupe.srv.cs.cmu.edu sci.crypt:15260 alt.security:9957 comp.org.eff.talk:16880 comp.security.misc:3389 comp.org.acm:1606 comp.org.ieee:1538Newsgroups: sci.crypt,alt.security,comp.org.eff.talk,comp.security.misc,comp.org.acm,comp.org.ieeePath: cantaloupe.srv.cs.cmu.edu!rochester!news.crd.ge.com!uunet!usc!venice!gumby.dsd.trw.com!trwacs.fp.trw.com!trwacs!johnsonFrom: johnson@trwacs.fp.trw.com (Steve Johnson)Subject: Re: Once tapped, your code is no good any more.Message-ID: <johnson.735025464@trwacs>Organization: TRW Systems Division, Fairfax VAReferences: <1993Apr17.032828.14262@clarinet.com> <tcmayC5M2xv.JEx@netcom.com>Distribution: naDate: Sat, 17 Apr 1993 05:44:24 GMTLines: 65tcmay@netcom.com (Timothy C. May) writes:>Brad Templeton (brad@clarinet.com) wrote:>: It occurs to me that if they get a wiretap order on you, and the escrow>: houses release your code to the cops, your code is now no longer secure.>: >: It's in the hands of cops, and while I am sure most of the time they are>: good, their security will not be as good as the escrow houses.>: >: What this effectively means is that if they perform a wiretap on you,>: at the end of the wiretap, they should be obligated to inform you that>: a tap was performed, and replace (for free) the clipper chip in your>: cellular phone so that it is once again a code known only to the>: escrow houses.>Getting the court order to reveal the key *also* makes decipherable>all *past* conversations (which may be on tape, or disk, or whatver),>as I understand the proposal. I could be wrong, but I've seen no>mention of "session keys" being the escrowed entities.>As the EFF noted, this raises further issues about the fruits of one>bust leading to incrimination in other areas.>But is it any worse than the current unsecure system? It becomes much>worse, of course, if the government then uses this "Clinton Clipper">to argue for restrictions on unapproved encryption. (This is the main>concern of most of us, I 